    "instruction": "Using metric.csv (parse timestamp as UTC datetimes), do the following in one atomic step:\n1) Identify which of the candidate components [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service] appear in metric.csv and list them.\n2) For each appearing component, for each kpi_name for that component, compute the global P95 value using the full available series for that component-kpi.\n3) Then filter the metric rows to the incident window 2024-02-20 15:31:23 to 2024-02-20 16:01:23 UTC and for each component-kpi produce a compact table with columns: component, kpi_name, global_p95, rows_in_window, rows_exceeding_p95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO UTC) or null if none. Limit output to the component-kpi rows that exist (max 100 rows). Return results as plain text or a small dataframe printout." }

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global P95 thresholds for each component–KPI (using the full series) and filtered metric data to the incident window. Summary shows 35 component–KPI combinations across the five candidate services, each with 25 rows in the window and typically 2 rows exceeding P95. Example earliest anomaly timestamps: ts-auth-service cpu at 2024-02-20T15:34:00Z, ts-auth-service diskio at 2024-02-20T15:51:00Z, ts-travel-service mem at 2024-02-20T15:57:00Z, ts-travel-service socket at 15:56, workload at 15:48. These raw counts do not yet distinguish isolated spikes from sustained faults or indicate severity (how much they breach thresholds). To identify true faults we must (for each component–KPI) find whether anomalies in the incident window form consecutive runs (faults), compute severity (max value vs global P95), and record earliest fault start times. This will narrow candidate root-cause component(s) to then inspect traces and logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv (timestamps parsed as UTC datetimes) and the previously computed global P95 per component–KPI, for each component–kpi that exists do the following in one atomic step:\n1) In the incident window 2024-02-20 15:31:23 to 2024-02-20 16:01:23 UTC, mark anomaly points where value > global_p95.\n2) Compute per component–kpi: rows_in_window, rows_exceeding_p95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO UTC or null), max_value_in_window, breach_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95) / global_p95 (use null or 0 if global_p95 == 0), number_of_consecutive_anomaly_runs, longest_run_length, start_timestamp_of_longest_run (ISO UTC or null).\n3) Return a compact table sorted by longest_run_length desc then breach_ratio desc. Limit output to top 50 rows. Provide results as plain text or a small dataframe printout with the specified columns." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis shows significant anomalies concentrated on ts-order-service and ts-travel-service: trace.to_ts-order-service.row_count has many exceedances (earliest 15:34 UTC) and trace.to_ts-order-service.duration_p95 shows a large breach (max 2.067s, breach_ratio ≈ 2.24, earliest 15:47 UTC). trace.to_ts-travel-service also shows elevated row_count and latencies beginning ~15:34 UTC, and traces emitted from ts-travel-service show elevated durations. Metric analysis previously found brief metric breaches on several services with the strongest metric deviations on ts-train-service and ts-travel-service, while many component–KPIs had only short 1–2 minute bursts. Combined, traces indicate a traffic surge involving ts-travel-service and ts-order-service, with order-service experiencing the largest latency increase (very large breach_ratio). According to the localization rules, when multiple services at the same level are faulty, the root cause is typically the most downstream faulty service in the trace call chain. We need to confirm that ts-order-service itself shows metric-level faults (resource KPIs) that could explain the latency (e.g., high CPU, memory, diskio, socket). To proceed, we should inspect metric KPIs specifically for ts-order-service (compact summary) to see which resource shows significant breaches during the incident window and their severity/timing.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Provide a compact metric-level fault summary for ts-order-service only. Using metric.csv (timestamp as UTC datetimes) and the previously computed global P95 per component–KPI, for ts-order-service produce a table with columns: kpi_name, global_p95, rows_in_window, rows_exceeding_p95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO UTC or null), max_value_in_window, breach_ratio = (max - global_p95)/global_p95 (or null/0 if global_p95==0), longest_run_length, start_timestamp_of_longest_run (ISO UTC or null). Sort by breach_ratio desc then longest_run_length desc. Limit output to all ks for ts-order-service (should be small). Return as a small dataframe or plain text table." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace analysis. Metrics: multiple services (train, travel, route, order, auth) show brief metric spikes (mostly 1–2 minutes). ts-order-service shows short latency spikes and modest resource breaches (latency-90 breach_ratio ~0.19, but resource KPIs show only tiny relative increases). Traces: the largest and most sustained anomalies are on traces to ts-order-service (high row_count and large duration_p95 breaches, many exceedances) and on traces to/from ts-travel-service (elevated row_count and durations starting ~15:34 UTC). The trace pattern suggests a traffic surge associated with ts-travel-service that translated into higher incoming row_count for ts-order-service; order-service experienced increased latency afterwards (notably at ~15:47 UTC) but its resource KPIs do not show sustained saturation. ts-travel-service itself shows stronger metric deviations (notably cpu breach_ratio ~0.55, latency breach ratios ~0.32–0.39, and trace duration breaches) and earlier anomalies (~15:34 UTC). According to the localization rules: when multiple service-level faults appear, the root cause is typically the most downstream faulty service in the trace chain — but only among services that are actually faulty. Here, travel-service shows both traffic and resource/trace anomalies earlier and more severely, while order-service shows larger observed latency (the downstream symptom) but little resource saturation. That pattern indicates ts-travel-service is the originating faulty service (upstream) causing downstream overload on ts-order-service. The likely failure reason (from the allowed set) that best matches the telemetry is high CPU usage on ts-travel-service causing degraded service behavior and increased downstream traffic/latency. However, we should validate with logs for ts-travel-service (and ts-order-service) to confirm whether logs show errors or increased operation counts consistent with a traffic surge or CPU saturation before finalizing.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv (parse timestamp as UTC datetimes), perform a compact log-level anomaly summary for ts-travel-service and ts-order-service only. For each of these two components and for each log_name present, compute the global P95 using the full available series, then filter to the incident window 2024-02-20 15:31:23 → 2024-02-20 16:01:23 UTC and return a table with columns: component, log_name, global_p95, rows_in_window, rows_exceeding_p95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO UTC or null), max_value_in_window, breach_ratio = (max - global_p95)/global_p95 (or null/0 if global_p95==0). Limit output to at most 20 rows. Return as a small dataframe or plain text table." }

